# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: animal-welfare
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:animal-welfare/a-cow-at-my-table] It covers the conflict between animal rights advocates and the meat industry, and their respective attempts to influence consumers.
[src:animal-welfare/a-cow-at-my-table] It was directed, shot, and edited by Jennifer Abbott, who spent five years travelling across Canada, the United States, Australia and New Zealand to interview representatives on all sides.
[src:animal-welfare/a-cow-at-my-table] The film intercuts these interviews with images of farm animals and industrial farming operations.
[src:animal-welfare/a-cow-at-my-table] It explores what is sometimes popularly called factory farming.
[src:animal-welfare/a-cow-at-my-table] The filming of *A Cow at My Table* drew early criticism from the Canadian meat industry, with both the Ontario Chicken Marketing Board and the Dairy Farmers of Ontario publishing articles warning of Abbott's actions.
[src:animal-welfare/a-cow-at-my-table] Music for the film was performed by Oh Susanna.
[src:animal-welfare/a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals] The book was reviewed in contemporary periodicals including the *London Medical Gazette*, *The Athenaeum*, and *The Veterinary Record*.
[src:animal-welfare/a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals] It was later noted by writers including Henry S.
[src:animal-welfare/a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals] Ralph Fletcher (1780—1851) was a surgeon based in Gloucester.
[src:animal-welfare/a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals] He studied at St Bartholomew's Hospital in London and received an M.D. from the University of Edinburgh Medical School.
[src:animal-welfare/a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals] He held appointments at the Gloucester Infirmary, Dispensary, and Lunatic Asylum.
[src:animal-welfare/a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals] He published medical papers on the relation between mental and physical health.
[src:animal-welfare/a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals] Fletcher was twice elected Mayor of Gloucester and served as president of the local branch of the Society for the Prevention of Cruelty to Animals in Gloucester.
[src:animal-welfare/a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals] He lived on Barton Street, near the city's animal pound, and his observations of the animals kept there were said to have inspired *A Few Notes on Cruelty to Animals*.
[src:animal-welfare/a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals] In a brief "Preliminary Note", Fletcher writes about the suffering of animals, especially those dependent on humans.
[src:animal-welfare/a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals] He rejects the view that animals are insensible to pain or that their suffering is divinely ordained, and argues for compassion on moral and theological grounds.
[src:animal-welfare/a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals] In "Importance of the Subject", Fletcher draws on his experience as president of the Society for the Prevention of Cruelty to Animals in Gloucester.
[src:animal-welfare/a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals] He writes that public acts of cruelty form only a small part of a wider problem, and that abuse often takes place in private spaces such as stables, slaughterhouses, and homes.
[src:animal-welfare/a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals] He argues that existing legislation was inadequate, because small fines and judicial discretion to reduce sentences did not deter offenders.
[src:animal-welfare/a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals] The main part of the book consists of notes on individual animals and practices.
[src:animal-welfare/a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals] Fletcher describes donkeys as animals commonly subjected to overwork and neglect.
[src:animal-welfare/a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals] He condemns blood sports such as shooting tied cocks and badger-baiting.
[src:animal-welfare/a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals] His discussion of cats and dogs contrasts their treatment: he writes that cats were often tormented or killed for amusement, while dogs suffered from starvation, beatings, cart-work, and fighting.
[src:animal-welfare/a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals] Fletcher criticises methods used in the rearing and slaughter of calves and lambs, including starvation and repeated bleeding to produce white veal.
[src:animal-welfare/a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals] He writes about overwork, neglect, and abandonment, and argues that owners as well as drivers should be held legally responsible.
[src:animal-welfare/a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals] Fletcher ends by calling for tougher penalties for cruelty, official oversight of slaughterhouses and stables, wider public instruction in humane treatment, and hospitals for sick and injured animals.
[src:animal-welfare/a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals] A review in the *London Medical Gazette* described the book as the work of a hospital surgeon acquainted with suffering.
[src:animal-welfare/a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals] The reviewer agreed with Fletcher's criticism of animal experimentation, but called his proposal for hospitals for animals a "somewhat Utopian scheme" said to have some precedent in the East.
[src:animal-welfare/a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals] Salt in the "Bibliography of Animal Rights" section of his 1892 work *Animals' Rights: Considered in Relation to Social Progress*, where he referred to it as a treatise on animal cruelty.
[src:animal-welfare/a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals] In his 1989 reference work *Keyguide to Information Sources in Animal Rights*, Charles R.
[src:animal-welfare/a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals] Magel described *A Few Notes on Cruelty to Animals* as an early account of animal abuse in the Gloucester area and noted its proposal for hospitals for animals modelled on human institutions.
[src:animal-welfare/a-fleshless-diet] Buttner obtained his M.D. from Yale Medical School in 1909 and received the Campbell Gold Medal for the highest rank on his examination and the Keese Prize for his thesis.
[src:animal-welfare/a-fleshless-diet] In 1916, Buttner was described by the editor of the *Journal of the American Medical Association* as a "recognized representative in the literature of vegetarianism." He argued for vegetarianism from a scientific basis.
[src:animal-welfare/a-fleshless-diet] Buttner practiced medicine in New Haven, Connecticut.
[src:animal-welfare/a-fleshless-diet] He was a member of the New Haven County Medical Association.
[src:animal-welfare/a-fleshless-diet] Buttner is best known for his vegetarian book *A Fleshless Diet*, published in 1910.
[src:animal-welfare/a-fleshless-diet] It was widely reviewed in medical journals with a mixed response.
[src:animal-welfare/a-fleshless-diet] Buttner argued that comparative anatomy and nutrition demonstrates that man is suited for a fleshless diet and that meat is dangerous and unnecessary.
[src:animal-welfare/a-fleshless-diet] His recommended diet consisted of vegetables, eggs and milk.
[src:animal-welfare/a-fleshless-diet] Buttner wrote that "It is not illogical for vegetarians to use milk and eggs, as these animal products are distinctly less toxic than meat and also less likely to be disease-laden.
[src:animal-welfare/a-fleshless-diet] A review in the *American Physical Education Review*, praised the book for compiling useful dietetic research but commented that it failed to show scientific discretion in the selected material.
[src:animal-welfare/a-fleshless-diet] A review in the *Journal of the American Medical Association* recommended the book as a reference work whether or not one accepts Buttner's conclusions.
[src:animal-welfare/a-fleshless-diet] A review in *The Medical Standard*, noted that the book was a "piece of special pleading for the propaganda which it is designed to promote […] We may say this, however, for Dr.
[src:animal-welfare/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] Salt was active in a number of reform causes in the late 19th century, including prison reform, education, socialism, and animal protection.
[src:animal-welfare/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] He later founded the Humanitarian League in 1891.
[src:animal-welfare/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] In *A Plea for Vegetarianism and Other Essays*, he argued that a vegetarian diet was humane, economical, and practicable, and challenged common objections to abstention from meat.
[src:animal-welfare/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] Across these essays, Salt defends vegetarianism on ethical, social, and economic grounds.
[src:animal-welfare/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] He argues against the killing of animals for food, disputes the view that meat is necessary for health, and links diet to wider questions of conduct and social reform.
[src:animal-welfare/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] Several essays also attack blood sports and reply to objections made by critics of vegetarianism, including Sir Henry Thompson.
[src:animal-welfare/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] Themes developed in *A Plea for Vegetarianism and Other Essays* appeared again in Salt's later writings, including *Animals' Rights: Considered in Relation to Social Progress* (1892).
[src:animal-welfare/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] At a social meeting organised by the London Vegetarian Society on 20 November 1931, Gandhi said that Salt's *A Plea for Vegetarianism* had shown him that vegetarianism was "a moral duty" and not only a matter of custom or personal vow.
[src:animal-welfare/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Robert Morris (1703–1754) was an English writer on architecture.
[src:animal-welfare/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] His published works include *Lectures on Architecture* (1734–36), *An Essay on Harmony* (1739), and *The Art of Architecture* (1742).
[src:animal-welfare/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] He also wrote poems, essays, and pamphlets, and worked as a surveyor.
[src:animal-welfare/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] According to Adams, Morris encountered *A Dissertation on the Voluntary Eating of Blood* in 1745.
[src:animal-welfare/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Expecting an argument against flesh-eating, he instead found a defence of meat consumption based on a post-Flood reading of Genesis.
[src:animal-welfare/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Morris disagreed with that interpretation and wrote a reply, which was published in 1746 as *A Reasonable Plea for the Animal Creation*.
[src:animal-welfare/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] The treatise is made up of a preface, a letter to General Foliot, nine letters addressed to a friend, and a concluding reply to *A Dissertation on the Voluntary Eating of Blood*.
[src:animal-welfare/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Adams writes that the central part of the book consists of letters Morris had written in 1737 and 1738 and later incorporated into the printed work.
[src:animal-welfare/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Morris argues that humans have no natural right to kill animals for food.
[src:animal-welfare/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] He appeals both to Genesis and to "the nature and reason of things", maintaining that the food originally given to humans was the produce of the earth.
[src:animal-welfare/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] He rejects attempts to justify meat-eating through scripture, custom, bodily necessity, or animal predation.
[src:animal-welfare/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] He also argues that humans are not naturally fitted for carnivory, and describes butchery and cookery as artificial practices rather than natural ones.
[src:animal-welfare/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Drawing on writers such as Pythagoras and Plutarch, he attributes feeling and a degree of rationality to animals and treats their destruction for food as a matter of cruelty and injustice.
[src:animal-welfare/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] In her introduction to the 2005 republication, Carol J.
[src:animal-welfare/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Adams describes the treatise as a neglected contribution to 18th-century vegetarian and animal-ethical writing.
[src:animal-welfare/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] She argues that Morris' case against flesh-eating is centred less on health than on moral obligation, and that his appeal to the "light of Nature" gives the work a distinctive place among early vegetarian texts.
[src:animal-welfare/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Adams also comments on the book's epistolary form, noting that its letters are addressed to a flesh-eating friend.
[src:animal-welfare/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] She treats that structure as part of the book's argument, since Morris repeatedly answers objections and defends vegetarianism against the assumptions of a meat-eating society.
[src:animal-welfare/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] She further notes Morris' rejection of claims of human superiority and his attribution of sentience and reason to animals.
[src:animal-welfare/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] On Adams' reading, these features connect the treatise to later debates in animal ethics.
[src:animal-welfare/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Before its republication in 2005, the treatise had appeared only occasionally in modern writing.
[src:animal-welfare/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Whisker, John Simons, and Rod Preece each referred to it as an early contribution to vegetarian and animal-ethical thought.
[src:animal-welfare/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Simons described Morris, together with John Hildrop, as a precursor to Humphry Primatt.
[src:animal-welfare/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Preece quoted from the treatise and placed Morris among earlier writers who argued for vegetarianism on ethical grounds, including John Oswald, George Nicholson, Joseph Ritson, and John Frank Newton.
[src:animal-welfare/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] In 2005, the treatise was republished in *Organization & Environment* with an introductory article by Carol J.
[src:animal-welfare/a-sacred-duty] The film opens with footage of a NASA rocket launch, an animation of the Solar System, and a quote from Deuteronomy 30:19 about choosing between life and death (illustrated with images of Earth as seen from space, contrasted with an exploding atom bomb).
[src:animal-welfare/a-sacred-duty] This is followed by a statement that humanity has not been caring for the planet properly according to Jewish teachings, which precedes a section about ancient Jewish texts and sacred words that provide "specific instructions on how to be custodians of the world in which we live".
[src:animal-welfare/a-sacred-duty] Throughout the film, quotes from the Torah are contrasted with the various environmental threats facing humanity today; the quotes are also illustrated with close-ups of Hebrew scrolls, Jews praying, and scenes of nature.
[src:animal-welfare/a-sacred-duty] The Earth is again seen from space and the camera moves in to focus on Israel, which the narrator cites as a microcosm of current global problems related to air and water pollution, overpopulation, climate change, and health concerns.
[src:animal-welfare/a-sacred-duty] The film moves on to look at global problems, with scenes shot all over the world.
[src:animal-welfare/a-sacred-duty] The focus then shifts to the United States, where all the relevant issues are discussed in detail.
[src:animal-welfare/a-sacred-duty] Reference is made to *Livestock's Long Shadow*, a 2006 report by the Food and Agriculture Organization which claimed that livestock agriculture produces more greenhouse gases than all of the world's vehicles combined.
[src:animal-welfare/a-sacred-duty] Next comes a brief presentation, illustrated with simple animated charts, on how meat production is an inefficient way to produce food for a hungry world.
[src:animal-welfare/a-sacred-duty] This moves into footage of animal abuse on feedlots and in factory farms, and the pollution produced by these facilities.
[src:animal-welfare/a-sacred-duty] The film then focuses on the advantages of vegetarianism for reducing pollution and solving world hunger.
[src:animal-welfare/a-sacred-duty] With a change of diet toward vegetarianism, the film asserts that many of these environmental and health problems can be solved.
[src:animal-welfare/a-sacred-duty] After some fast-moving images of people and nature accompanied by music, the film ends with the same statement from Deuteronomy about "life and death" being narrated over a shot of a sunrise.
[src:animal-welfare/a-sacred-duty] The idea for the film was inspired by the writings of Richard H.
[src:animal-welfare/a-sacred-duty] Schwartz (*Judaism and Vegetarianism*, *Judaism and Global Survival*, etc.) who also served as associate producer.
[src:animal-welfare/a-sacred-duty] Schwartz had seen the Christian Vegetarian Association's 2006 film, *Honoring God's Creation*, and felt that a similar film would be effective in the Jewish community.
[src:animal-welfare/a-sacred-duty] At the time, he envisioned the film to be about 30 minutes long, though the final film ended up being 60 minutes long.
[src:animal-welfare/a-sacred-duty] Production began in 2005 with a basic proposal and outline in the JVNA's newsletter, along with a statement that Lionel Friedberg was willing to make the film for "a very low fee, basically to cover his costs".
[src:animal-welfare/a-sacred-duty] The film was funded by the JVNA through private contributions.
[src:animal-welfare/a-sacred-duty] Preliminary drafts of the script were circulated among members of the JVNA advisory committee and others for input, after which the script went through numerous revisions.
[src:animal-welfare/a-sacred-duty] Meanwhile, Schwartz and Friedberg set about interviewing possible participants and filming footage of nature in both Israel and the United States.
[src:animal-welfare/a-sacred-duty] The showing of slaughterhouse footage was controversial, with some members of a test audience in Staten Island seeing it as propaganda.
[src:animal-welfare/a-sacred-duty] Friedberg recalled, "Richard and I were accused of making a propaganda film for the vegetarian movement.
[src:animal-welfare/a-sacred-duty] We were accused of showing 'horrors that are impossible to watch'." However, he maintained that the graphic footage was necessary.
[src:animal-welfare/a-sacred-duty] In October and November 2007, *A Sacred Duty* was released direct-to-video and on DVD, with public showings in both Israel and the United States.
[src:animal-welfare/a-sacred-duty] Over 35,000 copies were distributed free of charge to synagogues, educational institutions, and individuals, complete with permission to show the film without having to pay the filmmakers any royalties.
[src:animal-welfare/a-sacred-duty] In addition, permission was granted to the public to duplicate and distribute the film free of charge.
[src:animal-welfare/a-sacred-duty] Numerous short excerpts from the film were edited and re-posted by various YouTube users, and the full version became available on YouTube in January 2008.
[src:animal-welfare/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] Francis Hutcheson (1694–1746) was a philosopher of the Scottish Enlightenment and professor of moral philosophy at the University of Glasgow.
[src:animal-welfare/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] He was a leading defender of moral sense theory, according to which moral judgement arises from an innate sense rather than from reason alone.
[src:animal-welfare/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] He began work on *A System of Moral Philosophy* in 1738 and continued revising it until his death.
[src:animal-welfare/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] In *A System of Moral Philosophy*, Hutcheson sets out a broad account of ethics, natural law, private rights, and political society.
[src:animal-welfare/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] The first book concerns human nature and the supreme good.
[src:animal-welfare/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] Hutcheson discusses the faculties of the mind, the affections, and the will, and restates his view that human beings possess a moral sense by which they approve virtue and disapprove vice.
[src:animal-welfare/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] He argues that virtue is grounded in benevolence directed by reason, and relates moral life to providence and natural religion.
[src:animal-welfare/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] The second book deals with natural law and private rights.
[src:animal-welfare/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] Hutcheson discusses obligation, contracts, property, promises, oaths, and legal duties.
[src:animal-welfare/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] He distinguishes between perfect and imperfect rights, and treats justice as distinct from broader duties of benevolence.
[src:animal-welfare/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] He also argues that laws should answer to reason, public good, and natural equity.
[src:animal-welfare/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] The third book turns to civil society and government.
[src:animal-welfare/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] Hutcheson examines the basis of political authority, the forms of government, and topics including marriage, family, slavery, taxation, magistracy, war, and civil law.
[src:animal-welfare/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] He holds that political power must be exercised for the common good and with the consent of the governed.
[src:animal-welfare/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] Modern commentators have drawn attention to Hutcheson's discussion of animals in the *System*.
[src:animal-welfare/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] In a 2007 article, Aaron Garrett argued that Hutcheson offered an early argument for animal rights by grounding moral consideration in sentience and the capacity to suffer rather than in rational agency alone.
[src:animal-welfare/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] Garrett also compared Hutcheson's treatment of animals with his discussion of infants, and placed him in a line of thought distinct from Lockean rights theory.
[src:animal-welfare/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] Michael Bradie likewise noted that Hutcheson treated cruelty to animals as morally wrong because animals are capable of suffering.
[src:animal-welfare/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] At the same time, Bradie argued that Hutcheson retained a hierarchical account in which human beings, because of their superior rational capacities, may use animals when necessary.
[src:animal-welfare/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] Bradie described this position as an early attempt to balance human interests with concern for animal suffering.
[src:animal-welfare/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] Foulis in Glasgow and distributed in London by A.
[src:animal-welfare/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] It appeared in two volumes in 1755, five years after Hutcheson's death; it was published posthumously by his son Francis Hutcheson the younger, from the original manuscript.
[src:animal-welfare/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] A new edition was published in 2000 by Thoemmes, with an introduction by Daniel Carey, and was later republished by A & C Black in 2006.
[src:animal-welfare/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] A further edition was issued by Cambridge University Press in 2015.
[src:animal-welfare/animal-welfare] Respect for animal welfare is often based on the belief that nonhuman animals are sentient and that consideration should be given to their well-being or suffering, especially when they are under the care of humans.
[src:animal-welfare/animal-welfare] These concerns can include how animals are slaughtered for food, how they are used in scientific research, how they are kept (as pets, in zoos, farms, circuses, etc.), and how human activities affect the welfare and survival of wild species.
[src:animal-welfare/animal-welfare] There are two forms of criticism of the concept of animal welfare, coming from diametrically opposite positions.
[src:animal-welfare/animal-welfare] One view, held by some thinkers in history, holds that humans have no duties of any kind to animals.
[src:animal-welfare/animal-welfare] The other view is based on the animal rights position that animals should not be regarded as objects and any use of animals by humans is unacceptable.
[src:animal-welfare/animal-welfare] Accordingly, some animal rights proponents argue that the perception of better animal welfare is used as an excuse for continued exploitation of animals.
[src:animal-welfare/animal-welfare] Some authorities therefore treat animal welfare and animal rights as two opposing positions.
[src:animal-welfare/animal-welfare] Others see animal welfare gains as incremental steps towards animal rights.
[src:animal-welfare/animal-welfare] A new study has devised a unique way to dissociate conscious from nonconscious perception in animals.
[src:animal-welfare/animal-welfare] The researchers built experiments predicting opposite behavioral outcomes to consciously vs. non-consciously perceived stimuli.
[src:animal-welfare/animal-welfare] The monkeys' behaviors displayed these exact opposite signatures, just like aware and unaware humans tested in the study.
[src:animal-welfare/animal-welfare] Animal protection laws were enacted as early as the 1st millennium BCE in India.
[src:animal-welfare/animal-welfare] Several Indian kings built hospitals for animals, and emperor Ashoka (304–232 BCE) issued orders against hunting and animal slaughter, in line with *ahimsa*, the doctrine of nonviolence.
[src:animal-welfare/animal-welfare] The institutionalization of early animal welfare in the Indian subcontinent was profoundly shaped by Jainism, which elevated noviolence to its supreme ethical principle.
[src:animal-welfare/animal-welfare] Driven by the belief that all living beings possess a soul and the capacity to suffer, ancient Jain communities established the world's first widespread network of animal sanctuaries and charitable hospitals, known as *panjrapoles*.
[src:animal-welfare/animal-welfare] Funded primarily by wealthy Jain merchant guilds, these institutions were dedicated to sheltering, feeding, and medically treating sick, aging, and rescued animals, particularly cattle and birds, rather than euthanizing them.
[src:animal-welfare/animal-welfare] This highly organized Jain welfare framework deeply influenced the broader cultural and legislative approach to animal ethics throughout early Indian history.
[src:animal-welfare/animal-welfare] In the 13th century CE, Genghis Khan protected wildlife in Mongolia during the breeding season (March to October).
[src:animal-welfare/animal-welfare] In the Edo period of Japan, Tokugawa Tsunayoshi (1646 - 1709) instituted several laws relating to animal welfare, particularly towards dogs, earning him the nickname of "the dog Shogun".
[src:animal-welfare/animal-welfare] In 1776, English clergyman Humphrey Primatt authored *A Dissertation on the Duty of Mercy and Sin of Cruelty to Brute Animals*, one of the first books published in support of animal welfare.
[src:animal-welfare/animal-welfare] Since 1822, when Irish MP Richard Martin brought the "Cruel Treatment of Cattle Act 1822" through Parliament offering protection from cruelty to cattle, horses, and sheep, an animal welfare movement has been active in England.
[src:animal-welfare/animal-welfare] Martin was among the founders of the world's first animal welfare organization, the Society for the Prevention of Cruelty to Animals, or SPCA, in 1824.
[src:animal-welfare/animal-welfare] In 1840, Queen Victoria gave the society her blessing, and it became the RSPCA.
[src:animal-welfare/animal-welfare] The society used members' donations to employ a growing network of inspectors, whose job was to identify abusers, gather evidence, and report them to the authorities.
[src:animal-welfare/animal-welfare] In 1837, the German minister Albert Knapp founded the first German animal welfare society.
[src:animal-welfare/animal-welfare] One of the first national laws to protect animals was the UK Cruelty to Animals Act 1835 followed by the Protection of Animals Act 1911.
[src:animal-welfare/animal-welfare] In the US it was many years until there was a national law to protect animals—the Animal Welfare Act of 1966—although there were a number of states that passed anti-cruelty laws between 1828 and 1898.
[src:animal-welfare/animal-welfare] In India, animals are protected by the "Prevention of Cruelty to Animals Act, 1960".
[src:animal-welfare/animal-welfare] Significant progress in animal welfare did not take place until the late 20th century.
[src:animal-welfare/animal-welfare] In 1965, the UK government commissioned an investigation—led by professor Roger Brambell—into the welfare of intensively farmed animals, partly in response to concerns raised in Ruth Harrison's 1964 book, *Animal Machines*.
[src:animal-welfare/animal-welfare] On the basis of Brambell's report, the UK government set up the Farm Animal Welfare Advisory Committee in 1967, which became the Farm Animal Welfare Council in 1979.
[src:animal-welfare/animal-welfare] The committee's first guidelines recommended that animals require the freedom to "stand up, lie down, turn around, groom themselves and stretch their limbs." The guidelines have since been elaborated upon to become known as the Five Freedoms.
[src:animal-welfare/animal-welfare] In the UK, the Animal Welfare Act 2006 (c.
[src:animal-welfare/animal-welfare] 45) consolidated many different forms of animal welfare legislation.
[src:animal-welfare/animal-welfare] A number of animal welfare organisations are campaigning to achieve a Universal Declaration on Animal Welfare (UDAW) at the United Nations.
[src:animal-welfare/animal-welfare] In principle, the Universal Declaration would call on the United Nations to recognise animals as sentient beings, capable of experiencing pain and suffering, and to recognise that animal welfare is an issue of importance as part of the social development of nations worldwide.
[src:animal-welfare/animal-welfare] The campaign to achieve the UDAW is being coordinated by World Animal Protection, with a core working group including Compassion in World Farming, the RSPCA, and the Humane Society International (the international branch of HSUS).
[src:animal-welfare/animal-welfare] The 2019 UN Global Sustainable Development Report identified animal welfare as one of several key missing issues in the 2030 Agenda for Sustainable Development.
[src:animal-welfare/animal-welfare] hens (middle and bottom) which are given access to the outdoors.
[src:animal-welfare/animal-welfare] However, animal welfare groups argue that the vast majority of free-range hens are still intensively confined (bottom) and are rarely able to go outdoors.
[src:animal-welfare/animal-welfare] A major concern for the welfare of farmed animals is factory farming in which large numbers of animals are reared in confinement at high stocking densities.
[src:animal-welfare/animal-welfare] Biosecurity is also a risk with free range farming, as it allows for more contact between livestock and wild animal populations, which may carry zoonoses.
[src:animal-welfare/animal-welfare] Farmed animals are artificially selected for production parameters which sometimes impinge on the animals' welfare.
[src:animal-welfare/animal-welfare] For example, broiler chickens are bred to be very large to produce the greatest quantity of meat per animal.
[src:animal-welfare/animal-welfare] Broilers bred for fast growth have a high incidence of leg deformities because the large breast muscles cause distortions of the developing legs and pelvis, and the birds cannot support their increased body weight.
[src:animal-welfare/animal-welfare] As a consequence, they frequently become lame or suffer from broken legs.
[src:animal-welfare/animal-welfare] The increased body weight also puts a strain on their hearts and lungs, and ascites often develop.
[src:animal-welfare/animal-welfare] In the UK alone, up to 20 million broilers each year die from the stress of catching and transporting before reaching the slaughterhouse.This stress can be measured by the high level of heart rate and its cortisol levels, but it can also be seen in their behavior or physical changes.
[src:animal-welfare/animal-welfare] In situations where they are threatened, alone, or can't interact with others, these results are common.
[src:animal-welfare/animal-welfare] Animal welfare violations have been observed more in intensively bred chicken, pig and cattle species, respectively, and studies and laws have been enacted in this regard.
[src:animal-welfare/animal-welfare] However, animal welfare in semi-intensive species such as sheep and goats is nowadays being scrutinised and gaining importance.
[src:animal-welfare/animal-welfare] Another concern about the welfare of farmed animals is the method of slaughter, especially ritual slaughter.
[src:animal-welfare/animal-welfare] While the killing of animals need not necessarily involve suffering, the general public considers that killing an animal reduces its welfare.
[src:animal-welfare/animal-welfare] A 2023 report by the Animal Welfare Institute found that animal welfare claims by companies selling meat and poultry products lack adequate substantiation in roughly 85% of analyzed cases.
[src:animal-welfare/animal-welfare] Captive cetaceans are kept for display, research and naval operations.
[src:animal-welfare/animal-welfare] To enhance their welfare, humans feed them fish that are dead but are disease-free, protect them from predators and injury, monitor their health, and provide activities for behavioral enrichment.
[src:animal-welfare/animal-welfare] Some are kept in lagoons with natural soil and vegetated sides.
[src:animal-welfare/animal-welfare] Most are in concrete tanks which are easy to clean but echo their natural sounds back to them.
[src:animal-welfare/animal-welfare] They cannot develop their own social groups, and related cetaceans are typically separated for display and breeding.
[src:animal-welfare/animal-welfare] Military dolphins used in naval operations swim free during operations and training and return to pens otherwise.
[src:animal-welfare/animal-welfare] Captive cetaceans are trained to present themselves for blood samples, health exams, and noninvasive breath samples above their blow holes.
[src:animal-welfare/animal-welfare] Staff can monitor the captives afterward for signs of infection from the procedure.
[src:animal-welfare/animal-welfare] Research on wild cetaceans leaves them free to roam and make sounds in their natural habitat, eat live fish, face predators and injury, and form social groups voluntarily.
[src:animal-welfare/animal-welfare] However, boat engines of researchers, whale watchers and others add substantial noise to their natural environment, reducing their ability to echolocate and communicate.
[src:animal-welfare/animal-welfare] Electric engines are far quieter, but are not widely used for either research or whale watching, even for maintaining position, which does not require much power.
[src:animal-welfare/animal-welfare] Vancouver Port offers discounts for ships with quiet propeller and hull designs.
[src:animal-welfare/animal-welfare] Boat engines also have unshielded propellers, which cause serious injuries to cetaceans who come close to the propeller.
[src:animal-welfare/animal-welfare] The US Coast Guard has proposed rules on propeller guards to protect human swimmers, but has not adopted any rules.
[src:animal-welfare/animal-welfare] The US Navy uses propeller guards to protect manatees in Georgia.
[src:animal-welfare/animal-welfare] Ducted propellers provide more efficient drive at speeds up to 10 knots, and protect animals beneath and beside them, but need grilles to prevent injuries to animals drawn into the duct.
[src:animal-welfare/animal-welfare] Attaching satellite trackers and obtaining biopsies to measure pollution loads and DNA involve either capture and release, or shooting the cetaceans from a distance with dart guns.
[src:animal-welfare/animal-welfare] A cetacean was killed by a fungal infection after being darted, due to either an incompletely sterilized dart or an infection from the ocean entering the wound caused by the dart.
[src:animal-welfare/animal-welfare] Researchers on wild cetaceans have not yet been able to use drones to capture noninvasive breath samples.
[src:animal-welfare/animal-welfare] Other harms to wild cetaceans include commercial whaling, aboriginal whaling, drift netting, ship collisions, water pollution, noise from sonar and reflection seismology, predators, loss of prey, and disease.
[src:animal-welfare/animal-welfare] Efforts to enhance the life of wild cetaceans, besides reducing those harms, include offering human music.
[src:animal-welfare/animal-welfare] Canadian rules do not forbid playing quiet music, though they forbid "noise that may resemble whale songs or calls, underwater".
[src:animal-welfare/animal-welfare] In addition to cetaceans, the welfare of other wild animals has also been studied, though to a lesser extent than that of animals in farms.
[src:animal-welfare/animal-welfare] Research in wild animal welfare has two focuses: the welfare of wild animals kept in captivity and the welfare of animals living in the wild.
[src:animal-welfare/animal-welfare] The former has addressed the situation of animals kept both for human use, as in zoos or circuses, or in rehabilitation centers.
[src:animal-welfare/animal-welfare] The latter has examined how the welfare of non-domesticated animals living in wild or urban areas are affected by humans or natural factors causing wild animal suffering.
[src:animal-welfare/animal-welfare] He wrote that wild animals often have large offspring, with most of them dying young by starving or being eaten alive.
[src:animal-welfare/animal-welfare] According to Horta, the ethical reasons for wanting to improve human welfare also apply to wild animal welfare.
[src:animal-welfare/animal-welfare] The European Commission's activities in this area start with the recognition that animals are sentient beings.
[src:animal-welfare/animal-welfare] The general aim is to ensure that animals do not endure avoidable pain or suffering, and obliges the owner/keeper of animals to respect minimum welfare requirements.
[src:animal-welfare/animal-welfare] European Union legislation regarding farm animal welfare is regularly re-drafted according to science-based evidence and cultural views.
[src:animal-welfare/animal-welfare] For example, in 2009, legislation was passed which aimed to reduce animal suffering during slaughter and on 1 January 2012, the European Union Council Directive 1999/74/EC came into act, which means that conventional battery cages for laying hens are now banned across the Union.
[src:animal-welfare/animal-welfare] The Animal Welfare Act 2006 makes owners and keepers responsible for ensuring that the welfare needs of their animals are met.
[src:animal-welfare/animal-welfare] This law applies not only to pet owners but also to all industries involving animals, such as agriculture, entertainment, and research.
[src:animal-welfare/animal-welfare] Any activities and behaviors involving animals must comply with the welfare standards established by this law.
[src:animal-welfare/animal-welfare] These include the need: for a suitable environment (place to live), for a suitable diet, to exhibit normal behavior patterns, to be housed with, or apart from, other animals (if applicable), and to be protected from pain, injury, suffering and disease.
[src:animal-welfare/animal-welfare] Anyone who is cruel to an animal, or does not provide for its welfare needs, may be banned from owning animals, fined up to £20,000 and/or sent to prison for a maximum of six months.
[src:animal-welfare/animal-welfare] In the UK, the welfare of research animals being used for "regulated procedures" was historically protected by the Animals (Scientific Procedures) Act 1986 (ASPA) which is administrated by the Home Office.
[src:animal-welfare/animal-welfare] The Act defines "regulated procedures" as animal experiments that could potentially cause "pain, suffering, distress or lasting harm" to "protected animals".
[src:animal-welfare/animal-welfare] Initially, "protected animals" encompassed all living vertebrates other than humans, but, in 1993, an amendment added a single invertebrate species, the common octopus.
[src:animal-welfare/animal-welfare] Primates, cats, dogs, and horses have additional protection over other vertebrates under the Act.
[src:animal-welfare/animal-welfare] Revised legislation came into force in January 2013.
[src:animal-welfare/animal-welfare] This has been expanded to protect "...all living vertebrates, other than man, and any living cephalopod.
[src:animal-welfare/animal-welfare] Fish and amphibia are protected once they can feed independently and cephalopods at the point when they hatch.
[src:animal-welfare/animal-welfare] The ASPA also considers other issues such as animal sources, housing conditions, identification methods, and the humane killing of animals.
[src:animal-welfare/animal-welfare] Those applying for a license must explain why such research cannot be done through non-animal methods.
[src:animal-welfare/animal-welfare] The project must also pass an ethical review panel which aims to decide if the potential benefits outweigh any suffering for the animals involved.
[src:animal-welfare/animal-welfare] In the United States, a federal law called the Humane Slaughter Act was designed to decrease suffering of livestock during slaughter.
[src:animal-welfare/animal-welfare] The Georgia Animal Protection Act of 1986 was a state law enacted in response to the inhumane treatment of companion animals by a pet store chain in Atlanta.
[src:animal-welfare/animal-welfare] The Act provided for the licensing and regulation of pet shops, stables, kennels, and animal shelters, and established, for the first time, minimum standards of care.
[src:animal-welfare/animal-welfare] Additional provisions, called the Humane Euthanasia Act, were added in 1990, and then further expanded and strengthened with the Animal Protection Act of 2000.
[src:animal-welfare/animal-welfare] In 2002, voters passed (by a margin of 55% for and 45% against) Amendment 10 to the Florida Constitution banning the confinement of pregnant pigs in gestation crates.
[src:animal-welfare/animal-welfare] In 2006, Arizona voters passed Proposition 204 with 62% support; the legislation prohibits the confinement of calves in veal crates and breeding sows in gestation crates.
[src:animal-welfare/animal-welfare] In 2007, the Governor of Oregon signed legislation prohibiting the confinement of pigs in gestation crates and in 2008, the Governor of Colorado signed legislation that phased out both gestation crates and veal crates.
[src:animal-welfare/animal-welfare] Also during 2008, California passed Proposition 2, known as the "Prevention of Farm Animal Cruelty Act", which orders new space requirements for farm animals starting in 2015.
[src:animal-welfare/animal-welfare] In the US, every institution that uses vertebrate animals for federally funded laboratory research must have an Institutional Animal Care and Use Committee (IACUC).
[src:animal-welfare/animal-welfare] Each local IACUC reviews research protocols and conducts evaluations of the institution's animal care and use which includes the results of inspections of facilities that are required by law.
[src:animal-welfare/animal-welfare] The IACUC committee must assess the steps taken to "enhance animal well-being" before research can take place.
[src:animal-welfare/animal-welfare] According to the National Institutes of Health Office of Laboratory Animal Welfare, researchers must try to minimize distress in animals whenever possible: "Animals used in research and testing may experience pain from induced diseases, procedures, and toxicity.
[src:animal-welfare/animal-welfare] The Public Health Service (PHS) Policy and Animal Welfare Regulations (AWRs) state that procedures that cause more than momentary or slight pain or distress should be performed with appropriate sedation, analgesia, or anesthesia.
[src:animal-welfare/animal-welfare] However, research and testing studies sometimes involve pain that cannot be relieved with such agents because they would interfere with the scientific objectives of the study.
[src:animal-welfare/animal-welfare] The National Research Council's Guide for the Care and Use of Laboratory Animals also serves as a guide to improve welfare for animals used in research in the US.
[src:animal-welfare/animal-welfare] The Federation of Animal Science Societies' Guide for the Care and Use of Agricultural Animals in Research and Teaching is a resource addressing welfare concerns in farm animal research.
[src:animal-welfare/animal-welfare] Laboratory animals in the US are also protected under the Animal Welfare Act.
[src:animal-welfare/animal-welfare] The United States Department of Agriculture Animal and Plant Health Inspection Service (APHIS) enforces the Animal Welfare Act.
[src:animal-welfare/animal-welfare] Department of Agriculture (USDA), the total number of animals used in the U.S. in 2005 was almost 1.2 million, but this does not include rats, mice, and birds which are not covered by welfare legislation but make up approximately 90% of research animals.
[src:animal-welfare/animal-welfare] There are many different approaches to describing and defining animal welfare.
[src:animal-welfare/animal-welfare] John Webster defines animal welfare by advocating three positive conditions: Living a natural life, being fit and healthy, and being happy.
[src:animal-welfare/animal-welfare] Animal welfare often refers to a utilitarian attitude towards the well-being of nonhuman animals.
[src:animal-welfare/animal-welfare] It believes the animals can be exploited if the animal suffering and the costs of use is less than the benefits to humans.
[src:animal-welfare/animal-welfare] This attitude is also known simply as *welfarism*.
[src:animal-welfare/animal-welfare] An example of welfarist thought is Hugh Fearnley-Whittingstall's meat manifesto.
[src:animal-welfare/animal-welfare] Robert Garner describes the welfarist position as the most widely held in modern society.
[src:animal-welfare/animal-welfare] Welfarism is often contrasted with the animal rights and animal liberation positions, which hold that animals should not be used by humans and should not be regarded as human property.
[src:animal-welfare/animal-welfare] However, it has been argued that both welfarism and animal liberation only make sense if it is assumed that animals have "subjective welfare".
[src:animal-welfare/animal-welfare] It is a view that the best way to prevent animal suffering is to abolish the causes of animal suffering, but advancing animal welfare is a goal to pursue in the short term.
[src:animal-welfare/animal-welfare] Thus, for instance, new welfarists want to phase out fur farms and animal experiments but in the short-term they try to improve conditions for the animals in these systems, so they lobby to make cages less constrictive and to reduce the numbers of animals used in laboratories.
[src:animal-welfare/animal-welfare] Within the context of animal research, many scientific organisations believe that improved animal welfare will provide improved scientific outcomes.
[src:animal-welfare/animal-welfare] If an animal in a laboratory is suffering stress or pain it could negatively affect the results of the research.If a researcher wants to conduct an experiment, they must meet up with the 3R's (replacement, reduction, and refinement).
[src:animal-welfare/animal-welfare] They must show how they're going to put their plan into action.
[src:animal-welfare/animal-welfare] The ethics committee are to review the plan and check if all principles are being followed and ensure the benefits justify the harm of these animals.
[src:animal-welfare/animal-welfare] The 3R's are meant to lessen the use of animals in research and lessen any suffering.
[src:animal-welfare/animal-welfare] Increased affluence in many regions for the past few decades afforded consumers the disposable income to purchase products from high welfare systems.
[src:animal-welfare/animal-welfare] The adaptation of more economically efficient farming systems in these regions were at the expense of animal welfare and to the financial benefit of consumers, both of which were factors in driving the demand for higher welfare for farm animals.
[src:animal-welfare/animal-welfare] The volume of scientific research on animal welfare has also increased significantly in some countries.
[src:animal-welfare/animal-welfare] Some individuals in history have, at least in principle, rejected the view that humans have duties of any kind to animals.
[src:animal-welfare/animal-welfare] Animal rights advocates, such as Gary L.
[src:animal-welfare/animal-welfare] Francione and Tom Regan, argue that the animal welfare position (advocating for the betterment of the condition of animals, but without abolishing animal use) is inconsistent in logic and ethically unacceptable.
[src:animal-welfare/animal-welfare] Philosopher Steven Best suggests that an emphasis on "welfarism" has the effect of legitimizing "any human use of animals" so long as humans aren't "cruel" to them and do whatever is necessary to avoid inflicting "unnecessary harm".
[src:animal-welfare/animal-welfare] However, there are some animal right groups, such as PETA, which support animal welfare measures in the short term to alleviate animal suffering until all animal use is ended.
[src:animal-welfare/animal-welfare] According to PETA's Ingrid Newkirk in an interview with *Wikinews*, there are two issues in animal welfare and animal rights.
[src:animal-welfare/animal-welfare] "If I only could have one thing, it would be to end suffering", said Newkirk.
[src:animal-welfare/animal-welfare] "If you could take things from animals and kill animals all day long without causing them suffering, then I would take it...
[src:animal-welfare/animal-welfare] Everybody should be able to agree that animals should not suffer if you kill them or steal from them by taking the fur off their backs or take their eggs, whatever.
[src:animal-welfare/animal-welfare] Abolitionism holds that focusing on animal welfare not only fails to challenge animal suffering, but may actually prolong it by making the exercise of property rights over animals appear less unattractive.
[src:animal-welfare/animal-welfare] The abolitionists' objective is to secure a moral and legal paradigm shift, whereby animals are no longer regarded as property.
[src:animal-welfare/animal-welfare] In recent years documentaries such as watchdominion.com have been produced, exposing the suffering occurring in animal agriculture facilities that are marketed as having high welfare standards.
[src:animal-welfare/animal-welfare] World Organisation for Animal Health (OIE): The intergovernmental organisation responsible for improving animal health worldwide.
[src:animal-welfare/animal-welfare] World Animal Protection: Protects animals across the globe.
[src:animal-welfare/animal-welfare] World Animal Protection's objectives include helping people understand the critical importance of good animal welfare, encouraging nations to commit to animal-friendly practices, and building the scientific case for the better treatment of animals.
[src:animal-welfare/animal-welfare] They are global in a sense that they have consultative status at the Council of Europe and collaborate with national governments, the United Nations, the Food and Agriculture Organization and the World Organization for Animal Health.
[src:animal-welfare/animal-welfare] Animal Welfare Institute (AWI): An American non-profit charitable organization founded by Christine Stevens in 1951 with the goal of reducing suffering inflicted on animals by humans.
[src:animal-welfare/animal-welfare] It is one of the oldest animal welfare organizations in the US.
[src:animal-welfare/animal-welfare] Canadian Council on Animal Care: The national organization responsible for overseeing the care and use of animals involved in Canadian Science.
[src:animal-welfare/animal-welfare] Canadian Federation of Humane Societies (CFHS): The only national organization representing humane societies and SPCAs in Canada.
[src:animal-welfare/animal-welfare] They provide leadership on animal welfare issues and spread the message across Canada.
[src:animal-welfare/animal-welfare] The Canadian Veterinary Medical Association: Brings in veterinary involvement to animal welfare.
[src:animal-welfare/animal-welfare] Their objective is to share this concern of animals with all members of the profession, with the general public, with government at all levels, and with other organizations such as the CFHS, which have similar concerns.
[src:animal-welfare/animal-welfare] Compassion in World Farming: Founded over 40 years ago in 1967 by a British farmer who became horrified by the development of modern, intensive factory farming.
[src:animal-welfare/animal-welfare] "Today we campaign peacefully to end all cruel factory farming practices.
[src:animal-welfare/animal-welfare] They function as a donation guide for those seeking to help animals as much as possible with their donations.
[src:animal-welfare/animal-welfare] The Movement for Compassionate Living: Exists to- "Promote simple vegan living and self-reliance as a remedy against the exploitation of humans, animals and the Earth.
[src:animal-welfare/animal-welfare] Promote the use of trees and vegan-organic farming to meet the needs of society for food and natural resources.
[src:animal-welfare/animal-welfare] They host an online library of information about various animal-related subjects serving as a resource for groups and individuals dedicated to responsible animal care and well-being.
[src:animal-welfare/animal-welfare] National Farm Animal Care Council: Their objectives are to facilitate collaboration among members with respect to farm animal care issues in Canada, to facilitate information sharing and communication, and to monitor trends and initiatives in both the domestic and international market place.
[src:animal-welfare/animal-welfare] National Office of Animal Health: A British organisation that represents its members drawn from the animal medicines industry.
[src:animal-welfare/animal-welfare] Ontario Society for the Prevention of Cruelty to Animals: A registered charity comprising over 50 communities.
[src:animal-welfare/animal-welfare] Royal Society for the Prevention of Cruelty to Animals: A well-known animal welfare charity in England and Wales, founded in 1824.
[src:animal-welfare/animal-welfare] Universities Federation for Animal Welfare: A UK registered charity, established in 1926, that works to develop and promote improvements in the welfare of all animals through scientific and educational activity worldwide.
